observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Ensure the timely utilization of the LDRRMF in accordance with the approved LDRRMP and that the STF is utilized in accordance with Item 6.4 and 6.5 of the NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1;
b. Direct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Council (DRRMC) to identify the projects and activities to be charged out of the unexpended previous years’ LDRRMF and submit a revised AIP duly approved by the Local Sanggunian and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) upon recommendation of the LDRRMC in accordance with the approved LDRRMP;
c. Ensure that the LDRRMP includes the unexpended previous years’ LDRRMF;
d. Direct the LDRRMC to identify and prioritize PPAs that are feasible, doable and can be completed within the target date of implementation taking into consideration the thrust set by the LGU leadership;
e. Direct all concerned officials to optimize the utilization of LDRRMF focusing on programs, projects and activities that will strengthen its capacity to prevent and mitigate disaster risks; and
f. Facilitate proper monitoring and evaluation of the utilization of fund and assess its implementation to immediately address any arising concerns/problems that can be mitigated.

We recommend that management:

Create an Inventory Committee to ensure immediate conduct of physical inventory and the timely submission of RPCPPE in three (3) months;


Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) that details the specific tasks and responsibilities of the Committee members and a schedule outlining the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities. The PIP duly approved by the Local Chief Executive, should be submitted to the Audit Team, at least 10 CD before the scheduled start of the inventory taking activities;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to update property cards based on the results of the physical inventory and duly reconcile with accounting records to come up with the correct balances of PPE accounts;

Require the Municipal Accountant to annually provide depreciation and ensure proper allocation of depreciation that will cover all PPEs subject for valuation; and

Thereafter, direct the Inventory Committee to submit to the Audit Team the RPCPPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records, not later than the 10th day of January of the following year.

We recommend that management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer and reconcile records of prior years’ completed projects which are still included in the CIP; 

Direct the Municipal Engineer to validate status of identified completed projects booked as CIP with no details/schedules/undetermined status so that proper adjustments may be made to the CIP accounts;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to secure from the Municipal Engineer Certificate of Completion and Certificate of Turnover and Acceptance on the validated completed projects to be used as basis in the reclassification of the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE account; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to take up the corresponding depreciation expenses based on updated classified completed projects from the date of completion until December 31, 2022, and prepare adjusting entry as necessary to the appropriate asset accounts.

We recommend that management:

Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:

Maintain the necessary perpetual inventory records including the Supplies Ledger Cards for each commodity/stock in accordance with Section 114 of the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;

Record stock issuances only upon receipt of the SSMI with original copy of the Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS) pursuant to Sections 121 of NGAS for LGUs Vol. 1; 

Require the GSO/ Municipal Treasurer to:

Maintain stock cards for supplies to track their receipt and disposal, and reconcile them with the accounting unit's ledger cards; 

Consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI and submit it immediately, along with the RIS, to the Municipal Accountant for recording of the cost of the supplies and materials issued; and

Conduct a semestral physical count of inventory items by type, prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), and submit the results to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

We recommend that management:

Direct the Local Chief Executive to issue/cause the renewal of the contract of lease in CY 2022 to qualified lessees, and include in the terms and conditions, stipulations for the lessees compliance of its duties and responsibilities. Enforce compliance to the terms of contract before they are authorized to occupy the stall to protect the interest of the LGU; 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to strictly enforce collection of monthly stall rentals, as well as for the overdue amounts, impose surcharges from delinquent market stall holders and penalties set forth under the Revised Revenue Code of the Municipality;

Direct  the  Municipal Treasurer to  prepare Status Report of  Rental to include information on stall numbers existing occupants of rate/month, period of last payment and the total amount due; and

Strictly  comply  with  the  pertinent  Sections  of  the  2016  Revised  Revenue Code of the Municipality.

We recommend that management:

Allocate no less than 5% of the estimated revenue from regular sources annual appropriations for Disaster Risk Reduction Management activities in the LGU’s Annual Budget in compliance with NDRRMC - DBM and DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1;

Direct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Council to identify the projects and activities to be charged out of the unexpended previous years’ LDRRMF and incorporate, under a separate caption in the revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) duly approved by the Local Sanggunian and the Local Chief Executive (LCE); 


Direct the DRRMC to prioritize PPAs that are feasible and can be completed within the target date of implementation taking into consideration the thrust set by the LGU leadership; 

Direct all concerned officials to optimize the utilization of LDRRMF focusing on programs, projects and activities that will strengthen its capacity to prevent and mitigate disaster risks;

Facilitate proper monitoring and evaluation of the utilization of fund and assess its implementation to immediately address any concerns/ problems that may arise.

We recommend that management:

Provide annual appropriations for Gender and Development activities in the LGU’s Annual Budget amounting to at least 5% of the total budget appropriation in compliance with PWC-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01;

Strictly implement all projects, programs, and activities of its Gender and Development funds in relation to its Annual Budget and include only PPAs that are feasible and can be completed within the target date of implementation taking into consideration the priorities set by the LGU leadership;

Direct the GAD Focal person to determine the type of assistance, service to be extended, and its targeted recipients with the end view of resolving gender inequalities and come-up with internal rules as to ceiling amounts to be extended on social services and criteria for grants; and

Closely supervise PPAs implementation and to monitor its execution so problems/issues that may arise shall be immediately addressed.

We recommend that management:

Review and update the composition of the SWM Board as well as the LGU's SWM Plan as required under Section 16 of RA No. 9003, for purposes of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness, and relevance; 

Ensure that the updated SWM Plan is aligned and consistent with the national solid waste management framework, which specifies the projects and activities that would cover the SWM Plan's remaining years (CY 2023–2026);

c.	Enforce strict compliance with the significant provisions of RA No. 9003 and devise local ordinances relative to proper segregation, collection, transport, storage, treatment and disposal of solid waste; and

d.	Provide the allocation of funds for the required sanitary landfill and acquisition of SWM equipment and intensify the efforts to ensure the implementation of all PPAs relative to the Solid Waste Management Program of the LGU.

We recommended and the management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Health Officer and/or concerned RHU personnel to furnished the Municpal OIC-Accountant, the documents necessary to record the receipt and distribution of vaccines, ancillaries and supplies Inventory Report or its equivalent in relation to the vaccination program;
Direct the Municipal OIC-Accountant to record using the perpetual inventory system, the vaccines received and its distribution as reported by the LGU to DOH-CHD; and draw journal entry voucher for the applicable inventory accounts to record the remaining supplies of vaccines in stock at December 31,2021.

Instruct the Municaipal Accountant to immediately submit the aforementioned   supporting documents to enable the Audit Team to evaluate the Bayanihan to Grants to Cities and Municipalities (BGCM) transactions amounting to ₱7.124 million;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to thoroughly verify each disbursement as to the completeness and propriety of the supporting documents to strengthen internal control in the disbursement process; and

Adhere to the procedures and requirements provided in Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445, Item 9.2.5 of COA  Circular No. 2012-001  dated  June 14, 2012  and  GPPB  Circular  No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020 particularly in the conduct of emergency procurement under the Bayanihan Act.

